english:
  title: In Response to the Poem on Chongseok Pavilion
  author: An Chuk
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A thousand jagged stones rise into peaks of wonder,
    On azure cliffs the mist hangs thick as ink-wash painting.
    Where whale-tides surge, the sea foams white with frost,
    And mirage-breath floats high—pagodas shimmer, layer upon layer.

    On ancient steles the characters have worn to shadow,
    The gnarled roots of pines—from which age do they descend?
    By the rapids, the fisherman sits in his woven hat, bowing,
    Beneath the moon, the immortal in silk robes beckons—one might meet her.

    Yet alas, the throng of spirits has scattered like rain,
    And I grow weary watching common folk gather like clouds.
    Oh, to join the gulls and herons at the pavilion's edge,
    And sweep away all trace of dust from mortal footprints.
  footnotes:
    - Chongseok Pavilion (총석정) is a famous scenic site in Korea, known for its dramatic rock formations and historical significance.
    - The poem contrasts the ethereal, timeless beauty of the landscape with the mundane presence of ordinary humanity, reflecting the poet's yearning for transcendence and retreat from worldly affairs.
